We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The quadruple test results show low serum alpha-fetoprotein and unconjugated estriol, and high beta-hCG and inhibin A. This combination of results suggests an increased risk of Trisomy 21. Neural tube defects are associated with low levels of alpha-fetoprotein and high level of acetylcholinesterase. Congenital toxoplasmosis is associated with high levels of IgM and IgG antibodies. Trophoblastic disease is associated with high levels of beta-hCG.

The quadruple test measures levels of four substances in the mother’s blood, including alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), unconjugated estriol (uE3), beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (β-hCG) and inhibin A. In this case, low levels of AFP and uE3, combined with high levels of β-hCG and inhibin A, are indicative of an increased risk of trisomy 21 (Down syndrome).

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The results indicate a high risk of Trisomy 21. Alpha-fetoprotein and unconjugated estriol levels would be decreased in Trisomy 21, while beta-hCG and inhibin A levels would be increased. The patient's hCG level at 12 weeks of pregnancy was normal, so trophoblastic disease is unlikely. Consultation with a specialist and further testing may be advised to confirm the diagnosis.
